The Toll-like receptor 2/1 agonist PAM3 induces human monocytes to mature into immunosuppressive macrophages in vitro and in vivo. To examine the regulatory pathways used during PAM3- and M-CSFdriven macrophage maturation, the effect of inhibiting each pathway on the generation of MACinflam and MACsuppress was monitored. Inhibiting either Akt or the NF-kB complex reduced the general process by which monocytes differentiate into macrophages by 70 percent to 90 percent, leaving the remaining viable monocytes as the dominant cell type in those cultures (note that the generation of both CD163+ and CD163 macrophages was inhibited [P less than .01]; Figure 6B-C). By comparison, blockade of p38 MAPK or PTGS2 reduced the generation of CD163+ MACsuppress by 60 percent to 80 percent while increasing the frequency of CD163 MACinflam (P less than .01; Figure 6B-C. As expected, negative controls (PTGS1 and vehicle alone) had no effect on PAM3 - or M-CSFinduced monocyte differentiation (Figure 6B-C). These findings suggest that p38 MAPK and PTGS2 determine whether the macrophages generated via Akt- and NF-Bdependent pathways become proinflammatory or immunosuppressive.[PMID: 29296902]
